	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Tax crime in the fisheries sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												08 December 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A new OECD report was published in November, entitled ‘Evading the net: Tax crime in the fisheries sector’. It reinforces that analysing crime in the fisheries sector typically begins with the issue of illegal, unreported and unregulated (IUU) fishing. However, “wider criminal activity arises as a result of the same vulnerabilities that enable IUU fishing to take place – weak governance and enforcement in certain countries where fishing vessels are registered; the difficulty in identifying the beneficial owners of fishing companies and vessels, and logistical issues in tracking the activities of vessels at sea.”</p><p>The report looks at the impact of tax crime on the ability of countries to raise government revenue from their fisheries sector. The report insists that the whole fisheries value chain should be investigated to detect and combat tax crime, as “many of the documents that regulators and law enforcement authorities require from the participants in the horizontal value chain may also be important to the tax administration. However, in many cases tax examiners are not aware of the existence of such valuable information.”</p><p>The report examines the different types of tax crime that countries have identified as connected with the fisheries sector, including frauds in customs duties, incorrect declarations relating to the origin, and volume or categorisation of catches. The report highlights that “the effect of this tax loss on developing countries may be particularly great, impacting efforts to promote food security, reduce poverty and finance long term development.”</p><p>The report also discusses aspects of the fisheries sector that make it vulnerable, not only to tax crime but also to IUU fishing. In particular among these are the lack of transparency and the difficulty in obtaining beneficial ownership information, resulting from the prevalence of offshore companies and the practice of registering vessels under flags of convenience in countries other than those of their owners.</p><p>Finally, strategies available to administrations in preventing, detecting and combating tax offences are discussed; especially on how authorities and agencies dealing with fishing companies and other participants in the horizontal value chain cooperate and share information.</p><p>The annex to the report includes an outline of basic documentation that is produced at each stage of the value chain and which may be used by government officials in their work.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>OECD, Report ‘Evading the net: Tax crime in the fisheries sector’, November 2013</p><p class=" text-left">
<a href="http://www.oecd.org/tax/crime/evading-the-net-tax-crime-fisheries-sector.pdf" target="_self">http://www.oecd.org/tax/crime/evading-the-net-tax-crime-fisheries-sector...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>This report reminds us that IUU fishing, which draws a lot of international attention, is often linked to other criminal activities such as tax crime, which also affects the development prospects of ACP countries. One important aspect detailed in the report is the need to exchange information between the different authorities managing the various stages of the chain. For example, sharing and comparing fish-catch and fish-trade data may show discrepancies between declared and traded catches, revealing frauds, etc. Similar cooperation should also be developed at the international level – e.g. between ACP countries and the EU for the implementation of the EU IUU regulation – where data on vessels and companies licensed to fish should be exchanged. The report also rightly points out the necessity to increase transparency across the board, particularly regarding the beneficial owners of fishing operations – this is an area where cooperation should also be strengthened between the EU and ACP countries, in that some beneficial owners are of European origin, and some ACP states allow the opaque operations to take place under their flag.</p>
		</div>
		
